# Forbidden Commands

## Never Run — Git Destructive

- `git push --force` / `git push -f` (any branch)
- `git reset --hard`
- `git clean -fd` / `git clean -xfd`
- `git rebase` (rewrites history; suggest it but let the user run it)
- `git branch -D` (force-delete branches)
- `git checkout -- .` or `git restore .` on the whole repo (discards all changes)
- `git stash drop` / `git stash clear`

## Never Run — File System

- `rm -rf` on project root, `backend/`, `frontend/`, `deploy/`, `.cursor/`, `.git/`, or `node_modules/`
- `rm -rf /`, `rm -rf ~`, `rm -rf *` — never, under any circumstance
- Bulk `mv` or `cp` that could overwrite project directories
- `chmod -R` or `chown -R` on project directories
- `> file` (shell redirect that truncates a file to zero bytes)
- Deleting `package-lock.json` (causes dependency drift)

## Never Run — Process Management

- `kill`, `kill -9`, `killall`, `pkill` against processes you didn't start (especially SSH tunnels, port forwards, running dev servers in other terminals)
- Terminating any background process without asking first

## Never Run — Secrets & Credentials

- `cat .env`, `echo $GITHUB_TOKEN`, or any command that prints secrets, tokens, passwords, or API keys to the terminal
- `env` or `printenv` unfiltered (may dump secrets)
- Piping `.env` or secret files to any command's stdout
- Logging, printing, or embedding secrets in code, comments, or commit messages

## Never Run — Package & Registry

- `npm publish` / `npm unpublish`
- `npm audit fix --force` (can break dependencies; suggest it, don't run it)
- `docker push` to any registry
- `docker rm`, `docker rmi`, `docker system prune`, `docker-compose down -v` (wipes volumes/images)
- `npm link` in production directories

## Never Run — Git Push & PR

- `git push` to any remote without asking which remote and branch
- `gh pr create` without confirming the base branch, target repo, and title with the user first
- Never assume `origin/main` is the right target — ask

## Never Run — Remote Code Execution

- `curl ... | bash`, `wget ... | sh`, or any pipe-to-shell pattern
- `npx` with untrusted/unknown packages (only use well-known tools like `tsc`, `drizzle-kit`, `prettier`)

## Never Run — Network Exposure

- `python -m http.server`, `nc -l`, `php -S` or any command that serves local files on the network
- Binding services to `0.0.0.0` without asking

## Never Run — System-Level

- Modifying shell config files (`~/.zshrc`, `~/.bashrc`, `~/.gitconfig`)
- `sudo` anything
- `shutdown`, `reboot`, `dd`, `mkfs`, `fdisk` — system/disk operations
- Installing global packages (`npm i -g`, `brew install`) — suggest it, don't run it

## When in Doubt

If a command is destructive, irreversible, or touches things outside the project directory — **stop and ask**.
